This guide walks you through importing a CSV file into a MySQL table using the LOAD DATA LOCAL INFILE command. It covers enabling the required settings, writing the correct file path, and handling common date format issues.

Before You Start
You have MySQL installed (version 8.0 or later).

You have a CSV file to import (e.g., sales_orders.csv).

You have a target table already created in your database (e.g., sales_orders).

Step 1: Enable local_infile on the MySQL Server
Open a SQL query tab in MySQL Workbench (or use the command line) and run:
SET GLOBAL local_infile = 1;
To verify it worked:
SHOW VARIABLES LIKE 'local_infile';
Expected output: local_infile | ON
Note: This setting resets after a server restart. For a permanent change, add local_infile=1 to your MySQL configuration file (my.ini or my.cnf) and restart the server.

Step 2: Enable local_infile in Your MySQL Client
If using MySQL Workbench:
Go to the Home tab (where you see your database connections).

Right‑click your connection and choose Edit Connection.

Switch to the Advanced tab.

In the Others: text box, add this line:

OPT_LOCAL_INFILE=1
Click Test Connection, then OK.

Step 4: Write the LOAD DATA LOCAL INFILE Command
Here is a complete example. Adjust the column names and date format to match your CSV.

LOAD DATA LOCAL INFILE 'C:/temp/sales_orders.csv'   -- use forward slashes or double backslashes
INTO TABLE sales_orders
FIELDS TERMINATED BY ','
OPTIONALLY ENCLOSED BY '"'
LINES TERMINATED BY '\n'
IGNORE 1 LINES                     -- skip the header row
(@order_number, @order_date, @ship_date, @customer_name_index, @channel, 
 @currency_code, @warehouse_code, @delivery_region_index, @product_description_index, 
 @order_quantity, @unit_price, @unit_cost, @total_revenue)
SET
    order_number = TRIM(@order_number),
    order_date = STR_TO_DATE(TRIM(@order_date), '%e-%b-%y'),   -- convert '3-Feb-17' to DATE
    ship_date = STR_TO_DATE(TRIM(@ship_date), '%e-%b-%y'),
    customer_name_index = CAST(NULLIF(TRIM(@customer_name_index), '') AS UNSIGNED),
    channel = TRIM(@channel),
    currency_code = TRIM(@currency_code),
    warehouse_code = TRIM(@warehouse_code),
    delivery_region_index = CAST(NULLIF(TRIM(@delivery_region_index), '') AS UNSIGNED),
    product_description_index = CAST(NULLIF(TRIM(@product_description_index), '') AS UNSIGNED),
    order_quantity = CAST(NULLIF(TRIM(@order_quantity), '') AS UNSIGNED),
    unit_price = CAST(NULLIF(TRIM(@unit_price), '') AS DECIMAL(14,2)),
    unit_cost = CAST(NULLIF(TRIM(@unit_cost), '') AS DECIMAL(14,3)),
    total_revenue = CAST(NULLIF(TRIM(@total_revenue), '') AS DECIMAL(16,2));

Step 5: Run the Command
Reconnect to the database (close the connection tab and open a new one).
